Patch Set 1:

I initially tried putting the retry logic in one, common function.  That function took as an argument a lambda that did the specific I2C operation being attempted (read byte, write word, etc.).

The approach worked, but it more than doubled the execution time for one I2C operation.  It results in two additional function calls: one for the common function and one for the lambda.

In the phosphor-regulators application hundreds of I2C operations are done every second, so I did not want this enhancement to cause a large performance impact.

Patch Set 1:

This enhancement is needed because the regulators application is encountering sporadic I2C failures due to underlying hardware issues.  For example, there are known I2C issues with the A1 version of the ASPEED.

Thanks Joseph for the additional information.

> For IBM's use case, we want the USB port enablement to be tied together, so all ports are either enabled or all are disabled.
> Disambiguation: This is for controlling the BMC USBs, not host USBs.
> 
> I believe Redfish intends to be able to control each USB port independently, and will have a way to tie their enablement together to handle use cases and implementations.

I don't think this is as simple as you might expect it to be.

Attempting to disable all BMC USB ports is not particularly useful generally speaking.  I think we really need to model this at a dbus level as individual usb ports even if you want to disable them all for your own features.  

Most Intel systems have a USB connection between the BMC and the Host via the PCH and if you disable this, you will fundamentally break some handling on the machine.  We, at a minimum, need a way to keep those USB ports running while disabling any externally facing USB ports.  But, I don't think the Aspeed even has a concept of "externally facing" vs "internally facing" USB ports, as I suspect it is a matter of schematic alignment between the Aspeed chip and the PCH.

What is the value, to a customer, of "disabling a USB port" and what does that even look like?  Does that mean power is disable to the USB port?  Does that mean that the USB controller in hardware is disabled?  Does that mean that the kernel doesn't load the USB driver for the controller on that port?  Does it mean the kernel refuses to probe end-points and/or load drivers for them?  Does it mean that the kernel prohibits certain soft-function, like auto-mounting USB flash devices?  "Disabling a USB port" is, to me, ambiguous without definition of the intention.

Since Joseph is involved here, I suspect there is some security reason driving this feature.  Depending on how the previous paragraph is answered there are different implementations and attack vectors you might be solving for.  I think those should be documented.


I don't want to see this attached to the BMC dbus interface (Eddie asked the same).  Even though it might solve Joseph's immediate request, it isn't a particularly good way of modeling this.  If we went this way in general we'd end up with tons of state attached to the BMC interface.

I suggest looking at xyz/openbmc_project/Control/Service/Attributes.  Is there a reason that the USB function(s) cannot be modeled like other software "Services" which use this existing interface?

I don't believe the requirement to have an admin-controlled function to disable USB ports needs its own design document.  The general concept is to remove or disable interfaces which are not needed, to reduce the attack surface.  Specifically, a BMC system integrator can remove an interface so it is not present in the firmware image.  Or that system integrator can add a function to allow a BMC admin to enable and disable an interface.  IBM needs a function to allow a BMC admin to enable and disable the USB interface.  I assumed this requirement would be clear.

Why is it needed?  Some users require the USB ports to be disabled to comply with their internal security requirements.  I don't have any external specs to reference here.  Also, some existing IBM systems have a function to disable BMC USB ports, and we need systems built on OpenBMC to match that function. The “zero-day USB attacks” I know of are related to Windows and auto-play, not a fundamental breakage of the USB subsystem.  Hopefully we don’t have USB keys set to auto-mount as-is, but we especially better not allow execute out of them.  That alone would protect the BMC far beyond what Windows does by default.  Again, I don’t know what you really need done here, but it might be as simple as a setting to disable mounting of USB file systems?  

On the other extreme of “disable”, you could be looking to entirely disable all power and signals to the port.  Someone could probably construct a malicious USB key that fries ports by drawing or dumping too much current down various pins, using some capacitors, a few relays, and a Arduino.  Maybe your customers are wanting to harden the server against that kind of damage.  I don’t know.

This is why I ask what you want out of a “disable” and what you’re trying to accomplish.

I'd love his input.

My problem with the awk approach is that we're relying on an HTTP parser OpenBMC we wrote ourselves, which is a generally accepted anti-pattern, and difficult to get right.  That's not to say I question Miltons skills, but the tests there make me think that it hasn't had as rigorous of a testing as beast has.  Same goes for the URL parser.
Also, in that example, I see no mention of a timer, or body size limit, making it a great attack vector if someone is hoping to DOS attack the BMC.  We seem to be compiling regular expressions for each request?  That seems like a problem for the BMC startup times.
Most importantly, the AWK approach is 592 lines of security-impacting code the project now has to maintain.  This patchset is a net negative line count, due to some of the continued housekeeping of http_connection, and simplifying a lot of assumptions.

In this implementation, we have essentially the same security model as bmcweb-secure, and rely on a parser that's been fuzzed and tested heavily, as well as rely on the same code we already have to get right in the secure case.

With all of the above said, I'm happy to be told I've missed something.

In every other case you listed, it's an internal daemon talking to internal APIs, where mistakes aren't likely to become major security issues.  My point above was specifically about HTTP parsers when interacting directly to unauthenticated, possibly attacking clients.  It should be noted, I wish we could've used nginx, but the last time I prototyped it (a precursor to bmcweb), it was damn near impossible to write secure nginx plugins that did what OpenBMC needed.  I do get your point, we write a lot of openbmc-specific stuff, but my response wasn't intended to be a comment about the projects direction as a whole, simply that specific case, of a "security conscious" network API boundary, needed a lot of careful inspection.  We should strive to rely on as little openbmc code as we can in those situations.

This patchset is mostly using library functions, and wrapping them in the logic that OpenBMC needed to be compatible, hence why the patchset turned out to be 12 lines less than the old code.  I think that's a win for using things our libraries already provide instead of writing it ourselves.

One more note: I wish the telemetry service was a thin dbus wrapper around collectd with an rrd backend.  That would be ideal in my mind, and IMO openbmc has no unique requirements in that space that aren't covered already by that combo.  Unfortunately, I didn't write the current proposal.  Maybe I will if I have to review anymore MonitoringService code :-)

phosphor-hwmon and dbus-sensors are both relatively thin wrappers around hwmon.  I wonder if you could rewrite them as thin wrappers around lm-sensors;  I never really considered that, but it would be neat.
